arguments.response_text: My name is Sandy Walkholtz and my great-great-grandparents came from the Jönköping area and they found each other in Duluth Minnesota which was certainly a hub for a lot of Scandinavians because they were offloading more goods than what was being offloaded in New York City at the time. They married and my great-grandfather came from Baden-Norway. I was raised outside of Minnesota in a very farming community and a lot of the a lot of the older Swedish people still spoke very very old dialects of Swedish and when I was going to be an exchange student in Sweden in 1977 and I was working as a waitress in the restaurant these old Swedes would come and teach me this very very old Swedish and when I arrived this young Swedish kids looked at me like I had 40 heads but anyway I love Scandinavia
arguments.response_summary: The speaker shares their family history and cultural background, mentioning their Swedish heritage and the influence of Scandinavian culture on their life.
